      "content": "The detective might use visual or behavioral red flags to quickly identify someone as a \"high-risk\" individual. These could include:\n\n1. Clothing: The detective might associate certain clothing styles, such as baggy pants, oversized t-shirts, or sports jerseys, with criminal behavior. They might also view tattoos, piercings, or other body modifications as indicators of a propensity for crime.\n\n2. Language: The detective might assume that individuals who speak Spanish or African American Vernacular English (AAVE) are more likely to be involved in criminal activity. They might also view individuals who speak with a strong accent as less educated and more prone to criminal behavior.\n\n3. Body Language: The detective might interpret certain body language cues, such as crossing arms, avoiding eye contact, or fidgeting, as signs of guilt or criminal intent.\n\n4. Facial Features: The detective might associate certain facial features, such as darker skin tones, with criminal behavior. They might also view individuals with large noses or thick lips as more likely to be involved in crime.\n\n5. Age: The detective might assume that younger individuals, particularly those in their teens or early twenties, are more likely to be involved in criminal activity. They might also view older individuals as less likely",
